{
  "text": "Using an antibody to PMK-1 protein to analyse which tissues activate PMK-1, as determined by its relocalization to the nucleus [CITATION_1] , we observed that the PMK-1 kinase is activated in the intestine of germline-translation-defective mutants (Fig. 4a,b) . This immunostaining was absent from pmk-1(km25)-null mutant animals, demonstrating the specificity of the antibody ( Supplementary Fig. 2a-c) . Transgenic animals that express mCherry-labelled PMK-1 protein in the intestine under the vha-6 promoter confirmed the intestinal activation of PMK-1 observed with the antibody: mCherry-labelled PMK-1 protein was nuclearly localized in eft-3(q145);pmk-1(km25) when compared with pmk-1(km25) with similar levels of mCherry::PMK-1 expression ( Supplementary Fig. 2d ). Nuclear mCherry::PMK-1 in the intestine of eft-3(q145);pmk-1(km25) co-localized with the phosphop38 antibody staining, suggesting that the nuclear PMK-1 corresponds to activated PMK-1 ( Supplementary Fig. 2e ). Because expression of p38 MAPK only in the intestine of the eft-3(q145);pmk-1(km25) mutant, lacking PMK-1 in all other cell types, is sufficient to induce p38 MAPK activation and subsequent nuclear localization in the intestine, the PMK-1 acts in the intestine to transduce the signal of germline translation defects to somatic xenobiotic response.",
  "citation_candidates": [
